<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="130" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[189,334,906,932]" box="[189,334,906,932]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,906,932]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,906,932]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[189,694,953,1014]" box="[234,298,953,979]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,298,953,979]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[189,694,953,1014]" box="[189,694,987,1014]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">
Forewing length 
<quantity box="[389,534,987,1014]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" metricValueMax="6.1" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" unit="mm" value="5.8" valueMax="6.1" valueMin="5.5">5.5–6.1 mm</quantity>
. (
<figureCitation box="[554,622,988,1014]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-163@7.[189,1398,757,1889]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 3. Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, holotype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-015). A. Dorsal view. B. Head, lateral. C. Basal flagellomeres of right antenna. D. Three bulging metallic spots on the basal half of forewing. E. Hair pencil from base of subcosta, ventral. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452227" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452227/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
A–E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[188,1398,1053,1185]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">HEAD. Vertex and frons silvery metallic. Pale orange yellow scales behind compound eyes. Antenna with alternate rings of creamy white and brownish gray on basal two third, distal third brownish gray. Labial palpus creamy white on two basal segments; brownish gray scales with creamy white margin on third segment.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452237" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4452237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452237/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" startId="12.[189,232,1822,1848]" targetBox="[189,1398,1242,1784]" targetPageId="12">
<paragraph blockId="12.[189,1399,1822,2025]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,268,1822,1848]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">Fig. 8.</emphasis>
Geographic distribution of three Neotropical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heinemann" authorityYear="1877" box="[819,974,1822,1848]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Heliodinidae</taxonomicName>
. Red rectangle on left indicates the location in South America of the area enlarged on right. Circle = type locality of 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[1140,1399,1857,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1140,1399,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">Helioandesia tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[189,373,1893,1919]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in northern Chile. Triangles = distribution of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Meyrick, 1917)" baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[940,1348,1893,1919]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Aetole" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demarcha">
<emphasis box="[940,1141,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">Aetole demarcha</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Meyrick E." box="[1159,1339,1893,1919]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" pagination="61 - 66" refId="ref7150" refString="Meyrick E. 1917. Heliodinidae. Exotic Microlepidoptera 2: 61 - 66." type="journal article" year="1917">Meyrick, 1917</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the geographically nearest heliodinid species to 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[722,856,1929,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[722,856,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">H. tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[866,1049,1928,1954]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
on the western slopes of the Andes, in Peru. Square = type locality of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Meyrick, 1932)" baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[715,1217,1963,1989]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Lithariapteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loriculata">
<emphasis box="[715,1011,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">Lithariapteryx loriculata</emphasis>
(Meyrick, 1932)
</taxonomicName>
on the eastern slopes of the Andes of Bolivia, the morphologically nearest species to 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[1015,1146,1999,2024]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1015,1146,1999,2024]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="129">H. tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1153,1329,1999,2025]" pageId="12" pageNumber="129" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="13.[186,1398,265,538]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">THORAX. Variable proportion of silvery metallic and brownish gray with creamy white margin scales dorsally, brownish gray scales with wider creamy white margin latero-ventrally. Legs mainly concolorous with latero-ventral side of thorax. Forewing mostly covered by brownish gray with creamy white margin scales; five metallic silvery bulging spots with black proximal margin, three near costal margin, size progressively decreasing from base to apex, two near anal margin; small metallic silvery spot near tegula, slightly differentiated metallic silvery diagonal stripe from about middle of distal margin of discal cell to near costal margin; a few brownish orange scattered scales mainly on distal half; fringe brownish gray. Hindwing brownish gray; fringe concolorous.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[187,1398,577,639]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">ABDOMEN. Mainly brownish gray dorsally, lighter near posterior margin of each segment; scales brownish gray with creamy white margin ventrally.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[189,684,677,704]" box="[189,684,677,704]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">
GENITALIA (
<figureCitation box="[314,386,677,704]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[327,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[326,1261,319,1818]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 5. Male genitalia and eighth segment of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♂, paratype (IDEA- LEPI-2020-021). A. Male genitalia, ventral view, phallus removed. B. Phallus, lateral view. C. Tergum and pleural lobes of eighth segment. D. Socius, closed arrow in A. E. Small spine-like cornuti on the vesica, open arrow in A. F. Medial part of the cornutus. G. Coremata between pleural lobes of segment VIII and genitalia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452231/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). As described for genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[189,378,743,805]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,325,743,769]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Female</emphasis>
Similar to male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[189,684,843,870]" box="[189,684,843,870]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">
GENITALIA (
<figureCitation box="[314,386,843,870]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[191,234,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-92@10.[189,1398,559,1861]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 6. Female genitalia of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov., ♀, paratype (IDEA-LEPI-2020-024) A. Female genitalia, ventral view. B. Papillae analis. C. Ornamentation of the proximal part of the signum. D. Ornamentation of the distal part of the signum. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452233/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). As described for genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="130" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[189,320,909,935]" box="[189,320,909,935]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,320,909,935]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,320,909,935]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Host plant</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[189,1399,955,1087]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">
The only known host plant is the native 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heimerl" authorityYear="1932" baseAuthorityName="Reiche" box="[677,861,955,981]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nyctaginaceae" genus="Mirabilis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[677,861,955,981]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Mirabilis acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[876,1052,955,982]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nyctaginaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Nyctaginaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1152,955,982]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,704,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-49@11.[189,1398,704,1852]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 7. Habitat and host plant ofHelioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov.A. The type locality near Zapahuira Village at about 3400 m elevation on the western slopes of theAndes of the Parinacota Province, northern Chile. B. The host plant Mirabilis acuta (Reiche) Heimerl (Nyctaginaceae). C. Detail of the damage pattern on a leaf of the host. D. Flower of M. acuta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452235/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
), a Chilean endemic (
<bibRefCitation author="Rodriguez R. &amp; Marticorena C. &amp; Alarcon D. &amp; Baeza C. &amp; Cavieres L. &amp; Finot V. L. &amp; Fuentes N. &amp; Kiessling A. &amp; Mihoc M. &amp; Pauchard A. &amp; Ruiz E. &amp; Sanchez P. &amp; Marticorena A." box="[199,456,991,1017]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" pagination="1 - 430" refId="ref7763" refString="Rodriguez R., Marticorena C., Alarcon D., Baeza C., Cavieres L., Finot V. L., Fuentes N., Kiessling A., Mihoc M., Pauchard A., Ruiz E., Sanchez P. &amp; Marticorena A. 2018. Catalogo de las plantas vasculares de Chile. Gayana Botanica 75: 1 - 430." type="journal article" year="2018">
Rodríguez 
<emphasis box="[328,386,991,1017]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). In the study zone 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heimerl" authorityYear="1932" baseAuthorityName="Reiche" box="[679,782,991,1016]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nyctaginaceae" genus="Mirabilis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[679,782,991,1016]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">M. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sprout and flower after the summer rains. The larvae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Vargas, 2021" authorityName="Vargas" authorityYear="2021" box="[220,350,1027,1052]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Helioandesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarregai" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[220,350,1027,1052]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">H. tarregai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[357,532,1026,1052]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
feed externally as leaf skeletonizers, remaining partially covered by a fine silk layer (
<figureCitation box="[313,406,1061,1087]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,704,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-49@11.[189,1398,704,1852]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 7. Habitat and host plant ofHelioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov.A. The type locality near Zapahuira Village at about 3400 m elevation on the western slopes of theAndes of the Parinacota Province, northern Chile. B. The host plant Mirabilis acuta (Reiche) Heimerl (Nyctaginaceae). C. Detail of the damage pattern on a leaf of the host. D. Flower of M. acuta." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452235/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="130" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[189,342,1126,1152]" box="[189,342,1126,1152]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,1126,1152]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1126,1152]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[189,1399,1173,1235]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[466,517,1174,1200]" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation box="[636,711,1173,1199]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[189,232,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1242,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-327@12.[189,1398,1242,1784]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 8. Geographic distribution of three Neotropical Heliodinidae. Red rectangle on left indicates the location in South America of the area enlarged on right. Circle = type locality of Helioandesia tarregai gen. et sp. nov. in northern Chile. Triangles = distribution of Aetole demarcha (Meyrick, 1917), the geographically nearest heliodinid species to H. tarregai gen. et sp. nov. on the western slopes of the Andes, in Peru. Square = type locality of Lithariapteryx loriculata (Meyrick, 1932) on the eastern slopes of the Andes of Bolivia, the morphologically nearest species to H. tarregai gen. et sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4452237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4452237/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), near Zapahuira, Parinacota Province, at about 
<quantity box="[1305,1399,1173,1200]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" pageId="13" pageNumber="130" unit="m" value="3400.0">3400 m</quantity>
elevation on the western slopes of the Andes of northern 
<collectingCountry box="[857,924,1208,1234]" name="Chile" pageId="13" pageNumber="130">Chile</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
